    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bush and the Books</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dallas Lea letter on William Safire's Sept 14 column says Gov George W Bush's frequent mispronunciations indicate he does not read much</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William Safire overlooks a key point about George W. Bush's frequent mispronunciations (''The Snickering Campaign,'' column, Sept. 14). Mr. Bush's errors tend to be ones of either adding a syllable to a word, or deleting one; these are characteristic of someone who has heard a word spoken but not encountered it in print.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William Safire overlooks a key point about George W. Bush's frequent mispronunciations (''The Snickering Campaign,'' column, Sept. 14). Mr. Bush's errors tend to be ones of either adding a syllable to a word, or deleting one; these are characteristic of someone who has heard a word spoken but not encountered it in print.</p>
        <p>Essentially, they indicate that he doesn't read much (or at least doesn't pay much attention to what he does read). Not everyone may agree that reading is an important activity for a president, and there's certainly no reason to be mean-spirited about these indications, but they do deserve to be brought to the public's attention.</p>
        <p>DALLAS LEA  Poughkeepsie, N.Y., Sept. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
